    </p>

    <p>
      As a part of my journey to master these frameworks, I have built several
      projects that utilize them in different ways:
    </p>

    <ul class="project-list">
      <li class="project-item">
        <div class="project-card">
          <div class="project-image">
            <img src="../assets/img/BluumLogo.png" alt="Bluum Logo" />
          </div>
          <div class="project-content">
            <p><strong>Bluum</strong></p>
            <p><small>A program developed in React Native.</small></p>
          </div>
          <div class="projectDesc">
            <p>
              Bluum is an app for children in inpatient care, focused on
              gamifying their hospital experience. Hospital staff (nurses,
              therapists, etc.) can assign patients tasks, and patients are
              rewarded with experience points and gems for completing them. They
              can then use their gems to purchase cosmetic items for their
              character, upgrade their character's house, and furnish their
              home.
            </p>

            <p>
              As the project continues to grow, we aim to expand the scope to an
              entire virtual town, similar to
              <a
                target="_blank"
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Club_Penguin"
                >Club Penguin</a
              >. Users would be able to interact with each other, show off their
              homes to their friends, and play minigames.
            </p>

            <p>
              This project was my first real foray into mobile app development,
              and it taught me a lot about user experience design and the unique
              challenges of building applications for touchscreen devices. In
              addition, it was my first major project in React Native, which
              created an entirely different set of challenges. While based in
              React, React Native has an entirely different structure, way of
              routing between pages, and way of saving reusable components.
            </p>

            <p>
              To learn more about Bluum, visit our
              <a target="_blank" href="https://www.bluumdesigns.com/">website</a
              >.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="project-item">
        <div class="project-card">
          <div class="project-image">
            <img
              src="../assets/img/MarkUp.png"
              alt="MarkUp Logo"
              style="max-width: 60%"
            />
          </div>
          <div class="project-content">
            <p><strong>MarkUp</strong></p>
            <p><small>A text editor web platform created using React, Marked.js, and Draft.js</small></p>
          </div>
          <div class="projectDesc">
            <p>
              MarkUp is an in-depth Markdown editor designed to allow devs to
              learn the ropes of Markdown. It provides a place where you can
              learn some of the basic Markdown syntax in a more familiar format.
              Using the app, you can quickly preview and edit your file, and
              export your file for your projects.
            </p>

            <p>
              Future plans include adding custom styles, user accounts, and file
              sharing. I also aim to implement full MD functionality, including
              nested bullets and links. Ultimately, the goal is to package the
              app and/or release it as a VSCode Extension.
            </p>

            <p>
              This project was a very good way for me to integrate other frameworks into React. It uses React.js as the base, but it also incorporates Marked.js to parse the Markdown syntax and Draft.js to scaffold the text editing functionality. This project was a great way for me to learn how to integrate different frameworks together, and it taught me a lot about how to use React as a base for building more complex applications. In addition, I used Electron.js to make the app into a desktop application, which was great practice for packaging and deploying apps.
